  "text": "First, prior to 1998, the terms \"restaurant revenue management\" and \"revenue per available seat hour\" (RevPASH) did not exist. In ground-breaking work in the CHQ, Professor Sherri Kimes and her colleagues applied the principles of yield management from the hotel and airline segments of our business to introduce the topic and start a line of research and a set of operations-based tools to better analyze, manage, and control revenue flow in restaurants [CITATION_1] . Through her work, Kimes demonstrated that by using a quantitative approach to examining operational and service processes, you can identify operational areas needing improvement. This requires a blend of scientific management, optimization, a keen understanding of how your operation works, and knowing your guests' attitudes and preferences regarding their service experiences. As I explain further in a moment, the key is to keep all these factors in view, as focusing on one area alone is never sufficient. Since then, CHQ has published well over thirty articles that have built on the concept of restaurant revenue management (cf. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
